Yes. It's an action which is attached to the view instance by vuex. The relevant part in main.vue is:
```js
    vuex: {
      getters: require('./vuex/getters.js'),
      actions: require('./vuex/actions.js'),
    },
  };
```

And, if I want to be really crazy, I can do that too:

```json
{
  "token indexers": {
    "words": "single_token",
    "tf-idf": "single_token"
  },
  "token embedder": {
    "words": "glove vectors",
    "tf-idf": "single_token_embedding with dim 1"
  }
}
```

While this would work, it may randomly pick a partition (from candidateLocs) that has common location with a (yet to be processed) partition from rdd(0); a better solution is:
1) First zip partitions with common locations as much as we can;
2) After we have zipped all the partitions with common locations, we can then process the remaining partitions (which have no common locations with others); we can simply zip them together in order (just as ZippedPartitionsBaseRDD does).
